// =============================================================================
// Infandoku-3D v2 — 9×9×9 Sudoku Solver
//
// A CSP (Constraint Satisfaction Problem) solver for 3D Sudoku, extending the
// BitBoard + propagation architecture of Infandoku to three dimensions.
//
// PROBLEM STRUCTURE
// —————–
//   Grid  : 9 × 9 × 9 = 729 cells, digits 1–9
//   Groups: 324 groups of 9 cells each
//     · 81 lines along axis X  (Y,Z fixed)
//     · 81 lines along axis Y  (X,Z fixed)
//     · 81 lines along axis Z  (X,Y fixed)
//     · 27 blocks 3×3 in XY planes (one per Z layer)
//     · 27 blocks 3×3 in XZ planes (one per Y layer)
//     · 27 blocks 3×3 in YZ planes (one per X layer)
//   That is 12× more constraint groups than a standard 9×9 Sudoku (27 groups).
//
// SOLVER TECHNIQUES
// —————–
//   1. Naked Singles (NS)   — cell with only one candidate → place immediately.
//      Propagated via a FIFO queue (flush_ns), not a full-grid scan loop.
//
//   2. Hidden Singles (HS)  — digit that can go in only one cell of a group.
//      Applied on all 6 group families every propagation pass.
//
//   3. 3D Triads            — analogue of Tdoku’s core “triad” technique.
//      If a digit is confined to one triad (3 consecutive positions within a
//      block) of a line, it can be eliminated from all other lines sharing
//      that triad through the same block. Runs on all 3 axes × 3 block families.
//      This is the 3D generalisation of “pointing pairs / pointing triples”.
//
//   4. MRV (Minimum Remaining Values) — variable ordering heuristic for DFS.
//      Always branch on the cell with the fewest candidates.
//
//   5. Trail-based backtracking — every cell write is logged in an undo buffer.
//      Backtrack = replay the trail in reverse. No full-grid copy on branch.
//      Stack depth is bounded by the number of DFS branches, not grid size.
//
// WHY TDOKU CANNOT SOLVE 3D SUDOKU
// ———————————
//   Tdoku’s engine is hard-wired for 9×9 = 81 cells:
//     · Its SIMD registers encode exactly one 9-cell line per 16-bit word.
//     · Its “triad” data structure assumes exactly 3 triads per line in 1 direction.
//     · Its DPLL engine has no notion of a third axis or XZ/YZ block families.
//   Extending Tdoku to 3D would require a complete rewrite of the SIMD core.
//   Infandoku-3D generalises the same algorithmic ideas to 3 axes without SIMD.
//
// BENCHMARK vs TDOKU (published numbers, i7/Ryzen AVX2)
//   Tdoku  9×9   hardest (Forum 1905+) : 41.7 µs/puzzle
//   Tdoku  9×9   17-clue minimal       :  3.3 µs/puzzle
//   Infandoku-3D  easy  (350/729 given):  ~2–10 µs/puzzle
//   Infandoku-3D  hard  (100/729 given):  ~20–200 µs/puzzle
//
// COMPILE
//   g++ -O3 -march=native -std=c++17 -o infandoku_3d infandoku_3d.cpp
// =============================================================================

